nzo A. Crim]]\n|college=[[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]\n|undraftedyear=1999\n|pastteams=\n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|1999|2000}})\n|nflnew=\n|pfr=\n}}\n'''Larry Lovette Brown''' (born September 1, 1976) is a former [[American football]] [[tight end]] who played for the [[Tennessee Titans]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[University of Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BrowLa25.htm |title=Larry Brown Stats |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |accessdate=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/larrybrown/2499854/profile |title=Larry Brown, TE |publisher=Nfl.com |accessdate=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Larry}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football players]]\n\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:American football tight ends]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Larry}}\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larry_Brown_(tight_end,_born_1976)"}
{"title_page": "Beats Electronics", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Beats Electronics LLC\n| logo = [[File:Beats Electronics logo.svg|110px]]\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| founders = [[Dr. Dre]]<br />[[Jimmy Iovine]]\n| area_served = [[World]]wide\n| key_people = [[Luke Wood]] (President)<br />Matthew Costello (COO)<ref name=\"Inc\">{{cite web|title=What Beats' President Said About Expansion--Before Apple Bought It For $14 Pesos|url=http://www.inc.com/burt-helm/apple-buys-beats.html?cid=em01011week22day28a |work=[[Inc.com]]|publisher=Mansueto Ventures|accessdate=31 May 2014|first=Burt |last=Helm|date=28 May 2014}}</ref><br />[[will.i.am]] (partner)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/digital-and-mobile/6106526/beats-by-william-co-founding-and-cashing-in-with-jimmy|title=Beats By will.i.am: Co-Founding and Cashing In With Jimmy Iovine |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150415043755/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/digital-and-mobile/6106526/beats-by-william-co-founding-and-cashing-in-with-jimmy |archivedate= 2015-04-15 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><br />[[Noel Lee (executive)|Noel Lee]] (Investor)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/5981823/beat-by-dre-the-inside-story-of-how-monster-lost-the-world|title=Beat By Dre: The Exclusive Inside Story of How Monster Lost the World|first=Sam |last=Biddle|publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |work=[[Gizmodo]] |accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150110105523/http://gizmodo.com/5981823/beat-by-dre-the-inside-story-of-how-monster-lost-the-world|archivedate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n| industry = {{flatlist|\n*[[Sound recording and reproduction|Audio]]\n*[[Consumer electronics]]\n}}\n| products = {{flatlist|\n*[[Headphones]]\n*[[Bluetooth]]-enabled accessories\n*[[Loudspeaker|Speakers]]\n}}\n| revenue = [[US$]]1.5 billion (2013)<ref>{{cite news |last=Ong |first=Janet |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/12/arts/music/beats-music-enters-online-streaming-market.html |title=Algorithm for Your Personal Rhythm |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2014-01-14 |accessdate=2014-05-09 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140510182731/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/12/arts/music/beats-music-enters-online-streaming-market.html |archivedate=2014-05-10 }}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 700 ({{As of|2014}})\n| parent = [[HTC]] (2010-2014) (partial ownership)<br />\n[[Apple Inc.]] (2014\u2013present)\n| subsid = \n| vector_logo = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|2006}}\n| location_city = [[Culver City, California]], [[United States]]\n| origins = \n| homepage = [https://www.beatsbydre.com/ www.beatsbydre.com]\n}}\n'''Beats Electronics LLC''' (also known as '''Beats by Dr. Dre''', or simply '''Beats by Dre''') is a subsidiary of [[Apple Inc.]] that produces [[Sound recording and reproduction|audio]] products. Headquartered in [[Culver City, California]],<ref name=\"beatsbydre\">{{cite web |url=http://th.beatsbydre.com/on/demandware.store/Sites-beats-Intl-Site/th_TH/CustomerService-Company |title=About us section |accessdate=2013-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131227014659/http://th.beatsbydre.com/on/demandware.store/Sites-beats-Intl-Site/th_TH/CustomerService-Company |archivedate=2013-12-27 |df= dmy-all |website=beatsbydre.com }}</ref>{{third-party-inline|date=May 2014}} the company was founded by music producer and rapper [[Dr. Dre]] and [[Interscope Records]] co-founder<ref>Beats Electronics</ref>{{full citation needed|date=October 2018}} [[Jimmy Iovine]].\n\nThe subsidiary's product line is \nprimarily focused on [[headphones]] and [[loudspeaker|speakers]]. The company's original product line was manufactured in partnership with the AV equipment company [[Monster Cable Products]]. Following the end of its contract with the company, Beats took further development of its products in-house. In 2014, the company expanded into the online music market with the launch of a subscription-based streaming service, [[Beats Music]].\n\nIn 2011, [[NPD Group]] reported that Beats' market share was 64% in the U.S. for headphones priced higher than $100, and the brand was valued at $1 billion in September 2013.<ref name=guardian-carlylebillion>{{cite web|title=Dr Dre Beats valued at more than $1bn following Carlyle deal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/27/dr-dre-beats-1bn-carlyle-sale|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140516232041/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/27/dr-dre-beats-1bn-carlyle-sale |archivedate= 16 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=theage-bass />\n\nFor a period, the company was majority-owned by [[Taiwan]]ese [[smartphone]] maker [[HTC]]. The company reduced its stake to 25% in 2012, and sold its remaining stake back to the company in 2013. Concurrently, [[Carlyle Group]] replaced HTC as a minority shareholder, alongside Dr. Dre and Iovine in late 2013. On August 1, 2014, [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] acquired Beats for $3 billion in a cash and stock deal, the largest acquisition in Apple's history.\n\n== History ==\n=== Formation ===\n[[File:Dr. Dre at Coachella 2012 cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Dr. Dre]] (seen in 2012), company co-founder]]\n[[File:Jimmy Iovine & David Guetta.jpg|thumb|Jimmy Iovine and David Guetta]]\nThe company was formally established in 2006,<ref name=beatscrunch>{{cite web|title=Beats Electronics |url= http://www.crunchbase.com/organization/beats-by-dr-dre|work=CrunchBase|publisher=CrunchBase.com|accessdate=20 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521045821/http://www.crunchbase.com/organization/beats-by-dr-dre|archivedate=21 May 2014 }}</ref> a time when Iovine perceived two key problems in the music industry: the impact of [[Copyright infringement|piracy]] on music sales and the substandard audio quality provided by [[Apple, Inc.|Apple]]'s plastic earbuds. Iovine later recalled that Dre said to him: \"Man, it's one thing that people steal my music. It's another thing to destroy the feeling of what I've worked on.\" Iovine sought the opinions of musicians with \"great taste\", such as [[M.I.A. (rapper)|M.I.A.]], [[Pharrell Williams]], [[will.i.am]], and [[Gwen Stefani]] during the early developmental stage.<ref name=\"Burt\" /> Beats initially partnered with [[Monster Cable Products|Monster Cable]], an audio and video component manufacturer based in [[Brisbane, California]], to manufacture and develop the first Beats-branded products, and debuted its first product, ''Beats by Dr. Dre Studio'' headphones, on July 25, 2008.\n\nTo promote its products, Beats primarily relied on endorsements by [[pop music|pop]] and [[hip-hop music|hip-hop]] music performers, including [[product placement]] within [[music video]]s, and partnering with musicians and other celebrities to develop [[celebrity branding|co-branded]] products.<ref name=\"Burt\">{{cite web|title=How Dr. Dre's Headphones Company Became a Billion-Dollar Business|url=http://www.inc.com/audacious-companies/burt-helm/beats.html|work=[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]|publisher=Mansueto Ventures|accessdate=31 May 2014|author=Burt Helm|date=May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"bw-beats\">{{cite news |title=Beats Electronics Is Breaking Up with Monster |author=Cliff Edwards |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/beats-electronics-is-breaking-up-with-monster-01122012.html?campaign_id=rss_null |newspaper=[[Business Week]] |date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=13 January 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116122935/http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/beats-electronics-is-breaking-up-with-monster-01122012.html?campaign_id=rss_null |archivedate=16 January 2012 }}</ref><ref name=bbc-headphones>{{cite news|title=From Lemmy to Snooki, celebs are desperate to sell you headphones|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20970495|work=BBC|accessdate=27 August 2013|date=10 January 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130925052740/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20970495|archivedate=25 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=time-beats>{{cite news|title=How Dr. Dre Made $300 Headphones a Must-Have Accessory |url= http://business.time.com/2013/01/16/how-dr-dre-made-300-headphones-a-must-have-accessory/ |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate= 27 August 2013 |date= 16 January 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130824225748/http://business.time.com/2013/01/16/how-dr-dre-made-300-headphones-a-must-have-accessory/ |archivedate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Beats' use of endorsements by musicians helped the company aggressively target the [[Young adult (psychology)|young adult]] demographics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fields|first=Brandi|year=2014|title=Selling the Beat: Hip-Hop Culture and Product Branding Among Young Adults|url=http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1666&context=gs_rp |journal=[[Southern Illinois University]] |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160704041240/http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1666&context=gs_rp |archivedate= 2016-07-04 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== HTC purchase and non-renewal of Monster contract ===\nIn August 2010, mobile phone manufacturer HTC acquired a 50.1% majority share in Beats for $309 million. The purchase was intended to allow HTC to compete with other cellphone makers by associating themselves with the Beats brand,<ref name=md-htcsell /> as the purchase also granted HTC exclusive rights to manufacture smartphones with Beats-branded audio systems.<ref name=cnet-htc>{{cite web|last=Sandoval|first=Greg|title=HTC to acquire majority stake in Dr. Dre's Beats|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-31001_3-20090967-261/htc-to-acquire-majority-stake-in-dr-dres-beats/|publisher=[[CNET]]|accessdate=20 March 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120504072603/http://news.cnet.com/8301-31001_3-20090967-261/htc-to-acquire-majority-stake-in-dr-dres-beats/|archivedate=4 May 2012}}</ref> Despite its majority acquisition, HTC allowed Beats to operate as an autonomous company.<ref name=cnet-htc /> [[Luke Wood]], President of Beats in May 2014, joined the company in January 2010, when the company was a \"licensing business\". Wood had previously worked under Iovine at Interscope Records.<ref name=\"Inc\" />\n\nOn January 19, 2012, ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' reported that Beats and Monster would not renew their production contract and their partnership ceased at the end of 2012. Dre and Iovine subsequently decided to oversee the entire operation of the company, from manufacturing to R&D,<ref name=\"Inc\" /> and aimed to double its workforce to around 300 employees. Monster would ultimately begin marketing its own competing line of premium headphones aimed towards an older demographic.<ref name=\"bw-beats\" /> At the time, neither Dre, Iovine or Wood were experienced in the operation of a company at such a grand level, but Wood explained in 2014:<blockquote>I didn't have manufacturing experience, but I had experience of building something from scratch \u2026 Every time we put out an album, it was basically like building a new business--a unique cast of characters, unique challenges and opportunities, and trying to figure out a unique path to market.<ref name=\"Inc\" /></blockquote>\n\nIn October 2012, Beats unveiled its first two self-developed products, \"Beats Executive\" headphones and \"[[Beats Pill]]\" wireless speakers\u2014Iovine believed that the company would now have to \"control [its] own destiny\" in order to continue its growth. Iovine also commented on how other headphone makers had attempted to emulate Beats' celebrity endorsement business model (including Monster themselves, who unveiled [[Earth, Wind and Fire]] and [[Miles Davis]]-themed headphones at the 2012 [[Consumer Electronics Show]]),<ref name=\"bw-beats\" /> stating that \"some of our competitors are cheap engineers who have never been to a recording studio. You can't just stick someone's name on a headphone that doesn't know anything about sound.\"<ref name=\"bw-beats\" /><ref name=billboard-destiny>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Iovine on Beats by Dre Parting With Monster: 'We Have to Control Our Own Destiny' |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/511582/jimmy-iovine-on-beats-by-dre-parting-with-monster-we-have-to-control-our-own |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130817062349/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/511582/jimmy-iovine-on-beats-by-dre-parting-with-monster-we-have-to-control-our-own|archivedate=17 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=billboard-firstinhouse>{{cite web|title=Beats By Dre Debuts First Post-Monster Cable Products|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1083371/beats-by-dre-debuts-first-post-monster-cable-products|work=Billboard|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130905221257/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1083371/beats-by-dre-debuts-first-post-monster-cable-products |archivedate=5 September 2013}}</ref> Following the decision to transform Beats into an autonomous entity, the company's revenues reached the $1 billion mark, according to Iovine.<ref name=\"Inc\" />\n\n=== HTC sale and Beats Music ===\n[[File:Beats Music logo.svg|200px|alt=The logo that Beats Music, a subsidiary of Beats Electronics, uses.|thumb|The logo for Beats Music.]]\nIn July 2012, HTC sold back half of its stake in Beats for $150 million, remaining the largest shareholder with 25.1 percent.<ref>{{cite news|title=HTC Just Sold Back Half Of Its Holdings In Beats Electronics|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/htc-just-sold-back-half-oin-beats-electronics-2012-7|accessdate=21 November 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=24 July 2012|author=Jonathan Standing & Clare Jim|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209044953/http://www.businessinsider.com/htc-just-sold-back-half-of-its-holdings-in-beats-electronics-2012-7|archivedate=9 December 2012}}</ref> The sale was intended to provide \"flexibility for global expansion while maintaining HTC's major stake and commercial exclusivity in mobile\".<ref name=md-htcsell>{{cite news|title=After HTC Sale, Dr. Dre and Jimmy Iovine Gain Control of Beats Headphones |url= http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/after-htc-sale-dr-dre-and-jimmy-iovine-gain-control-of-beats-headphones/ |work= Media Decoder|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=26 July 2012|first=Ben|last=Sisario|date=23 July 2012 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120726003018/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/after-htc-sale-dr-dre-and-jimmy-iovine-gain-control-of-beats-headphones/|archivedate=26 July 2012}}</ref> In August 2013, reports surfaced that Beats' founders planned to buy back HTC's remaining minority stake in the company, and pursue a new, unspecified partner for a future investment.<ref name=guardian-beatshtcout>{{cite web|title=Dr Dre's Beats to pull plug on HTC in favour of new business partner |url= https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/aug/19/dr-dre-beats-htc-new-partner|work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status= live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821145755/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/aug/19/dr-dre-beats-htc-new-partner|archivedate=21 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=bloomberg-htcbeats>{{cite web|title=Straight Outta HTC: Beats Audio May Have a New Solo Project|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-08-20/straight-outta-htc-beats-audio-may-have-a-new-solo-project|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130823071842/http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-08-20/straight-outta-htc-beats-audio-may-have-a-new-solo-project|archivedate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2013, HTC confirmed that it would sell its remaining 24.84% stake in Beats back to the company for $265 million. Concurrently, Beats announced that the [[Carlyle Group]] would make a $500 million minority investment in the company.<ref name=wsj-carayleears /><ref>{{cite news|title=HTC to Sell Back Stake in Beats Electronics for $265 Million |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-27/htc-to-sell-back-stake-in-beats-headphone-maker-for-265-million.html|accessdate=29 September 2013|newspaper=[[Bloomberg LP]]|date=27 September 2013|first=Yu-Huay |last=Sun|first2=Edmond |last2=Lococo |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130929145907/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-27/htc-to-sell-back-stake-in-beats-headphone-maker-for-265-million.html|archivedate=29 September 2013}}</ref> The overall deal valued Beats Electronics at $1 billion<ref name=guardian-carlylebillion /> and helped HTC turn a [[net profit]] of $10.3 million for the fourth quarter of 2013, following HTC's first quarterly loss in company history.<ref name=verge-beatssaleprofit>{{cite web|title=HTC narrowly avoids second quarterly loss by selling Beats stake|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/5/5275894/htc-narrowly-avoids-second-quarterly-loss-by-selling-beats-stake|work=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=24 January 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140124014911/http://www.theverge.com/2014/1/5/5275894/htc-narrowly-avoids-second-quarterly-loss-by-selling-beats-stake|archivedate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe appointment of a new [[chief operating officer]] (COO), a role previously filled by Wood,<ref name=\"Inc\" /> was announced in early November 2013. Matthew Costello, formerly of [[IKEA]] and HTC, was formally appointed to the role in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beats Electronics Names COO|url=http://www.labusinessjournal.com/news/2013/nov/06/beats-electronics-names-coo/|work=[[Los Angeles Business Journal]] |accessdate=8 November 2013|first=Natalie |last=Jarvey|date=6 November 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503115233/http://www.labusinessjournal.com/news/2013/nov/06/beats-electronics-names-coo/ |archivedate= 3 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=134391936&privcapId=65358694&previousCapId=65358694&previousTitle=Beats%20Electronics,%20LLC|title=Executive Profile Matthew Vincent Costello|last=|first=|date=31 May 2014|work=Bloomberg Businesweek|publisher=[[Bloomberg LP]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 21, 2014, the company launched Beats Music, a subscription-based online music streaming service.<ref name=verge-beatsmusicannounce /> Prior to the launch of the service, Beats stated that it intends to provide a different type of streaming experience to what was available on the market at the time. Additionally, the service would only be available to consumers in the U.S. at inception.<ref name=\"Gate\">{{cite web|title=Beats Music reveals launch details|url=http://www.commercegate.com/beats-music-reveals-launch-details/|work=CommerceGate|publisher=CommerceGate Ireland Ltd|accessdate=31 May 2014|date=23 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531162219/http://www.commercegate.com/beats-music-reveals-launch-details/|archivedate=31 May 2014}}</ref> Chief executive of Beats at the time, Ian Rogers, said:<blockquote>We wanted to build a music service that combined the freedom of an on-demand subscription service\u2014unlimited, uninterrupted streaming and downloads of tens of millions of songs \u2013 but layer on top features that would give you that feeling only music that moves you can give. The right song at the right time will give you a chill. Make you pull someone close. Nod your head. Sing in the mirror. Roll down the car window and crank the volume to the right.<ref name=\"Gate\" /></blockquote>\n\n=== Subsidiary of Apple Inc. (2014\u2013present) ===\nOn May 8, 2014, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] was in negotiations with Beats to purchase the company for $3.2 billion\u2014the largest purchase in Apple's history, ahead of its $429 million purchase of [[NeXT]] in 1996.<ref name=cnet-beatsapple>{{cite news|title=Apple said to be in talks to buy Beats Electronics for $3.2B |url= https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-said-to-be-in-talks-to-buy-beats-electronics-for-3-2b/|accessdate=9 May 2014|newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=9 May 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510134236/http://www.cnet.com/news/apple-said-to-be-in-talks-to-buy-beats-electronics-for-3-2b/|archivedate=10 May 2014}}</ref> The impending deal was prematurely and indirectly revealed in a photo and [[YouTube]] video posted to [[Facebook]] by [[Tyrese Gibson]] on May 8, 2014; the video documented a celebration in which Gibson and Dr. Dre made boasting remarks about the acquisition, with Dre declaring himself the \"first billionaire in hip hop\", while Gibson declared that the \"[[The World's Billionaires|Forbes list]]\" had changed. Both the photo and video were removed from Facebook the following morning, but both remain on Gibson's YouTube channel.<ref name=\"Inc\" /><ref name=cnet-tyrese>{{cite web|title='First billionaire in hip-hop' Dre boasts of Apple-Beats deal on Facebook |url= https://www.cnet.com/news/first-billionaire-in-hip-hop-dre-boasts-of-apple-beats-deal-on-facebook/|work=[[CNET]]|accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509132648/http://www.cnet.com/news/first-billionaire-in-hip-hop-dre-boasts-of-apple-beats-deal-on-facebook/|archivedate=9 May 2014}}</ref> Indeed, analysts estimated that the rumored deal would make Dr. Dre the first billionaire in the hip-hop music industry in terms of [[net worth]], assuming that he held at least 15% ownership in the company prior to the deal. Dr. Dre was listed with a net worth of $550 million on [[Forbes]]' ''[[The World's Billionaires]]'' 2014 list. It was also estimated that the [[Carlyle Group]] would receive a profit of $1 billion from the sale of its minority stake in the company.<ref name=wsj-carayleears>{{cite web|title=Apple's Beats Deal Is Music to Carlyle's Ears |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2014/05/08/apples-beats-deal-is-music-to-carlyles-ears/|work=MoneyBeat|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140509015946/https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2014/05/08/apples-beats-deal-is-music-to-carlyles-ears/ |archivedate=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=independent-drerichest>{{cite web|title=If Apple buys Beats Electronics for $3.2bn, will Dr Dre become hip hop's first billionaire?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/if-apple-buys-beats-electronics-for-32bn-will-dr-dre-become-hip-hops-first-billionaire-9343973.html|work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status= live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509145255/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/if-apple-buys-beats-electronics-for-32bn-will-dr-dre-become-hip-hops-first-billionaire-9343973.html|archivedate=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=wsj-drerichest>{{cite web|title=Could an Apple Beats Acquisition Make Dr. Dre the First Rap Billionaire?|url= https://blogs.wsj.com/corporate-intelligence/2014/05/08/will-apples-beats-deal-make-dr-dre-the-first-rap-billionaire/ |work=Corporate Intelligence|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140511214002/https://blogs.wsj.com/corporate-intelligence/2014/05/08/will-apples-beats-deal-make-dr-dre-the-first-rap-billionaire/|archivedate=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2014, Apple officially announced its intention to acquire Beats Electronics for $3 billion\u2014with $400 million to be paid in Apple stock and the remainder in cash. Some reports suggested that the reduction in value may have been a result of lower-than-expected subscriber numbers for the Beats Music service.<ref name=\"Inc\" /> Iovine felt that Beats had always \"belonged\" with Apple, as the company modeled itself after Apple's \"unmatched ability to marry culture and technology\". In regard to the deal, Apple CEO [[Tim Cook]] stated that \"Music is such an important part of all of our lives and holds a special place within our hearts at Apple. That's why we have kept investing in music and are bringing together these extraordinary teams so we can continue to create the most innovative music products and services in the world.\" Beyond stocking Beats products at its [[Apple Store|retail outlets]], Apple did not provide any further indications over how Beats would be integrated into its product line at the time, and whether Beats Music, which competed with Apple's own [[iTunes Radio]] service, would continue to operate after the acquisition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/05/28/apple-acquires-beats-electronics-for-3-billion/ |title=Apple acquires Beats Electronics for $3 billion |work=Engadget |date=May 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529084316/http://www.engadget.com/2014/05/28/apple-acquires-beats-electronics-for-3-billion/ |archivedate=May 29, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=verge-beatsappleconfirmed>{{cite web|title=Apple confirms it's buying Beats for $3 billion|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/5/28/5700530/apple-confirms-beats-acquisition|work=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=28 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140529051629/http://www.theverge.com/2014/5/28/5700530/apple-confirms-beats-acquisition |archivedate= 29 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=apple-pr>{{cite web|title=Apple to Acquire Beats Music & Beats Electronics |url= https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2014/05/28Apple-to-Acquire-Beats-Music-Beats-Electronics.html |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |accessdate= 28 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140528210544/http://www.apple.com/pr/library/2014/05/28Apple-to-Acquire-Beats-Music-Beats-Electronics.html |archivedate= 28 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe acquisition closed on August 1, 2014. To eliminate redundancy, Apple planned to lay off 200 workers from Beats' workforce of around 700.<ref name=OfficialClose>{{cite web|title=Apple closes $3B Beats deal, welcomes the company 'to the family' |url= https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-closes-3b-beats-deal-welcomes-the-company-to-the-family/|website=[[CNET]]|accessdate=1 August 2014 |url-status= live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802130730/http://www.cnet.com/news/apple-closes-3b-beats-deal-welcomes-the-company-to-the-family/|archivedate=2 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=bloomberg-jobcuts>{{cite web|title=Apple Said to Target 200 Job Cuts at Beats After Deal|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-07-30/apple-said-to-cut-200-jobs-at-beats-after-acquisition.html |website=[[Bloomberg LP]] |accessdate=1 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140801010755/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-07-30/apple-said-to-cut-200-jobs-at-beats-after-acquisition.html |archivedate=1 August 2014}}</ref> Beats Music was discontinued effective with the launch of [[Apple Music]] on June 30, 2015.<ref name=\"NYT WWDC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/apple-wwdc-2015/apple-music-does-everything-apple-says/ |accessdate=June 21, 2015 |title=Apple W.W.D.C. 2015: iOS 9, Apple Pay and Other Announcements |date= June 8, 2015 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150622124220/http://www.nytimes.com/live/apple-wwdc-2015/apple-music-does-everything-apple-says/ |archivedate=June 22, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=tc-beatsdiscontinued>{{cite web|title=Beats Music Tells Users To Switch To Apple Music|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/08/beat-it/|website=TechCrunch|publisher=AOL Inc. (Verizon Communications)|accessdate=3 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703164647/http://techcrunch.com/2015/06/08/beat-it/|archivedate=3 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Bose lawsuit ===\nIn July 2014, [[Bose Corporation]] sued Beats Electronics, alleging that its \"Studio\" line incorporated [[noise cancellation]] technology that [[patent infringement|infringed]] five patents held by the company. Bose has also sought an injunction which would ban the infringing products from being imported or sold in the United States.<ref name=time-beatslawsuit>{{cite web|title=Bose Is Suing Beats Over Headphone Patents|url=http://time.com/3036763/bose-beats-lawsuit/|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|accessdate=1 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140803015449/http://time.com/3036763/bose-beats-lawsuit/ |archivedate=3 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=wsj-soundoff>{{cite web|title=Sound Off: Bose Sues Beats Over Noise-Cancelling Patents |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/07/25/sound-off-bose-sues-beats-over-noise-cancelling-patents/|website=Digits|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=1 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140729143845/https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/07/25/sound-off-bose-sues-beats-over-noise-cancelling-patents/|archivedate=29 July 2014}}</ref> The lawsuit was settled out of court. Apple pulled all Bose products from its retail outlets, although it is unclear whether it was in response to the lawsuit, an [[ambush marketing]] conflict involving Beats and the [[NFL]] (which had recently named Bose as one of its official sponsors, and thus fined a player for displaying the Beats logo during an official activity), or as a result of Apple's acquisition of Beats.<ref name=verge-boseremoved>{{cite news|title=Apple has removed all Bose products from its store|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/10/17/6995403/apple-removes-bose-products-from-store |accessdate=17 October 2014|work=[[The Verge]]|date=17 October 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141018135935/http://www.theverge.com/2014/10/17/6995403/apple-removes-bose-products-from-store |archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref> However, two months later, Bose products returned to the shelves of Apple Stores. The companies settled in October 2014: details were not disclosed.<ref name=cnet-bosesettled>{{cite web|title=Apple's Beats, Bose settle patent spat over noise-canceling tech|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apples-beats-bose-settle-patent-spat-over-noise-canceling-tech/ |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150108005933/http://www.cnet.com/news/apples-beats-bose-settle-patent-spat-over-noise-canceling-tech/ |archivedate=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Monster lawsuit ===\nIn January 2015, [[Monster Cable|Monster Inc.]] sued Beats for [[fraud]], alleging that the company had used illicit tactics to force Monster out of the venture whilst retaining rights to the technologies and products that it had co-developed, and engaged in [[collusion]] to harm Monster's own audio products business. Monster argued that the acquisition of Beats by HTC and its founders' subsequent buyback was a \"sham\" to take control of Monster's stake in the company\u2014which could have been valued at over $100 million in the Apple purchase, that the company had \"concealed\" the role of Monster and its CEO [[Noel Lee (executive)|Noel Lee]] in the design and engineering of its products, and that \"had the partnership expired on its own terms, there would have been no transfer of Monster's years of work [onto the company]\". Monster also alleged that Beats had partaken in [[anti-competitive practices]] with retailers to force those offering Beats products to not offer Monster's competing products.<ref name=verge-monsterlawsuit>{{cite web |title= Monster sues Beats and co-founders Dr. Dre and Jimmy Iovine for fraud |url= https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/6/7505639/monster-suing-beats-and-co-founders-dr-dre-and-jimmy-iovine |website=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150107075249/http://www.theverge.com/2015/1/6/7505639/monster-suing-beats-and-co-founders-dr-dre-and-jimmy-iovine |archivedate=7 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=usatoday-monsterlawsuit>{{cite web|title=Tech firm Monster sues Beats and founders Dre and Iovine|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/01/06/monster-suit-beats-electronics/21355033/|website=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150107053857/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/01/06/monster-suit-beats-electronics/21355033/ |archivedate=7 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Beatrayed by Dre? Noel Lee says he built the headphones Apple paid $3 billion for. His take? $0. Now he's suing for his share.|work=[[Bloomberg LP]]|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2015-06-22/beatrayed-by-dre-|date=22 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160712212651/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2015-06-22/beatrayed-by-dre-|archivedate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that in retaliation for the lawsuit, Apple Inc. revoked Monster's membership in the [[MFi Program]] on May 5, 2015, meaning that Monster can no longer manufacture licensed accessories for [[iPhone]], [[iPod]] and [[iPad]] products, and must cease the sale of existing licensed products that contain the certification or technology licensed through the program by September 2015.<ref name=wsj-monsterrevoked>{{cite news|title=Apple Revokes Monster's Authority to Make Licensed Accessories|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-revokes-monsters-authority-to-make-licensed-accessories-1434481512 |accessdate=17 June 2015|work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150617004548/http://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-revokes-monsters-authority-to-make-licensed-accessories-1434481512 |archivedate=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe case was dismissed in August 2016, with a Supreme Court ruling that Beats \"had the right to terminate the agreement as of January 7th, 2013 or when there was a transaction resulting in a change of control of Beats\", and that Monster \"did not obtain the right to approve the change of control. Nor did the agreement require that any change of control had to be objectively reasonable\".<ref name=\"verge-monsterthrownout\">{{cite web|title=Monster's lawsuit against Beats has gone very poorly |url= https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/30/12719232/monster-beats-lawsuit-claims-dismissed-apple|website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=26 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161225171352/http://www.theverge.com/2016/8/30/12719232/monster-beats-lawsuit-claims-dismissed-apple |archivedate=25 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\n[[File:BeatsHeadphones-2 (47705430872).jpg|thumb|right|Example of Beats Headphones]]\nBeats' original product line were ''Beats by Dre'' headphones. In promotional materials, Dre outlined the line's advantages by alleging that listeners were not able to hear \"all\" of the music with most headphones, and that Beats would allow people to \"hear what the artists hear, and listen to the music the way they should: the way I do\". In comparison to most headphones, ''Beats'' products were characterized by an emphasis towards producing larger amounts of [[bass (music)|bass]], and are particularly optimized towards [[hip-hop music|hip-hop]] and [[pop music]].<ref name=theage-bass>{{cite news|title=How Beats by Dre knocked out better headphones|url=http://www.theage.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/how-beats-by-dre-knocked-out-better-headphones-20130913-2tola.html|work=The Age|accessdate=29 November 2013|location=Melbourne|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131120060243/http://www.theage.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/how-beats-by-dre-knocked-out-better-headphones-20130913-2tola.html|archivedate=20 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=cr-arebeatsworthit>{{cite web|title=Are Beats by Dr. Dre headphones worth the money?|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2013/05/are-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-worth-the-money/index.htm|publisher=Consumer Reports|accessdate=29 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204230212/http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2013/05/are-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-worth-the-money/index.htm|archivedate=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=geek-beats>{{cite web|last=Evans|first=Joel|title=Review: Beats by Dr. Dre headphones|url=http://www.geek.com/articles/gadgets/review-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-20080730/|publisher=Geek.com|accessdate=23 May 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428202630/http://www.geek.com/articles/gadgets/review-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-20080730|archivedate=28 April 2012}}</ref> In October 2012, Beats unveiled its first two self-developed products, the Beats Executive noise-cancelling headphones (to compete with similar offerings by [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] and [[Sennheiser]]) and the [[Beats Pill]] portable speaker.<ref name=\"bw-beats\" /><ref name=billboard-firstinhouse /> In October 2015, Beats launched a new collection of speakers including the upgraded Beats Pill+ Speaker.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beats Pill+ Speaker Launches Alongside New Colors for Solo2 Headphones|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2015/10/26/beats-pill-speaker-launches/|accessdate=29 October 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029002146/http://www.macrumors.com/2015/10/26/beats-pill-speaker-launches/|archivedate=29 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Headphones ===\n==== Beats Solo Pro ====\nThis is an on the ear style headphone. Along with the '''Powerbeats Pro''' true-wireless earphones, they are part of a new generation of Beats products made from the ground up with Apple. They are the first on-ear headphones made by Beats to feature [[active noise canceling]]. They are sold alongside the '''Solo 3'''. \n\n==== Beats Solo 3 Wireless ====\nThis is an on the ear style headphone. It can last for 40 hours on a single charge or indefinitely when plugged in via the headphone jack.\n\n==== Beats Studio 3 Wireless ====\nThis is currently the high-end wireless headphones that Beats offers. It connects by Bluetooth and has 40 hours of battery life, with 22 hours of battery life with adaptive noise cancelling on. It features Apple's [[Apple W series|W1 chip]] for quick connection to [[Apple device]]s running [[iOS 10]], [[macOS Sierra]], or [[watchOS 4]] or later. It also features pure adaptive [[noise cancelling technology]] which uses microphones both inside and outside the ear cups to measure sound levels based on the environment. If there is any headgear or eyewear on the user's head it calibrates the noise cancelling and volume level accordingly. It comes in a wide range of colors and editions, including black, blue and special collections such as the [[National Basketball Association|\"NBA]] Collection\".\n\n=== Earbuds ===\nOn September 7, 2016, '''Powerbeats\u00b3''' were released. On February 10, 2017, '''BeatsX''' neckband-style headphones were released.<ref>https://www.cnet.com/reviews/beatsx-earphones-review/</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Beats Replacement Parts, Ear Pads Cuashions & Headbands |date=2020-02-03|url=https://beatskinstore.com|work=Beats Replacement Parts|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> '''[[Powerbeats Pro]]''' were released on May 10, 2019, in the United States and 2 weeks later for UK and Europe.<ref>Cleo Clarkeson, [https://tenpire.com/meet-the-new-beats-powerbeats-pro/ \"Meet The New Beats Powerbeats Pro\"], ''Tenpire'', 10 April 2019.</ref>\n\n=== Beats Audio ===\nThe company has also licensed the Beats brand, under the name ''Beats Audio'' (rendered '''beats audio'''), and technology to other manufacturers. In 2009, [[Hewlett-Packard|HP]] began to offer [[personal computer]]s equipped with ''Beats Audio'' systems, beginning with its [[HP Envy]] line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www8.hp.com/us/en/hp-news/press-release.html?id=169479|title=HP News \u2013 HP and Beats Electronics Set New Premium Standard for Music Audio on Notebooks|work=hp.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402154046/http://www8.hp.com/us/en/hp-news/press-release.html?id=169479|archivedate=2015-04-02}}</ref> The system features a software [[Equalization (audio)|equalizer]] with a preset that HP marketed as being optimized for higher quality sound output.<ref name=\"hp-beats\">{{cite magazine |title=HP Envy 14: Plenty of Power in a Stylish Package |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/203364/hp_envy_14_plenty_of_power_in_a_stylish_package.html |magazine=[[PCWorld (magazine)|PC World]] |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323194853/http://www.pcworld.com/article/203364/hp_envy_14_plenty_of_power_in_a_stylish_package.html |archivedate=2012-03-23 }}</ref> Beats Electronics ceased its partnership with HP following its purchase by Apple Inc.; HP subsequently entered into a similar agreement with [[Bang & Olufsen]].<ref name=\"cnet-bando\">{{cite web|title=HP makes Bang & Olufsen its new audio partner|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/hp-makes-bang-olufsen-its-new-audio-partner/ |website=CNET|accessdate=21 February 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160226074822/http://www.cnet.com/news/hp-makes-bang-olufsen-its-new-audio-partner/|archivedate=26 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing its acquisition of a stake in the company, most new HTC smartphones began to be released with Beats Audio software, beginning with the [[HTC Sensation XE]]/XL with Beats Audio in September 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/09/14/htc-sensation-xe-gets-official-packing-1-5ghz-dual-core-cpu-and |title=HTC Sensation XE gets official, packing 1.5GHz dual-core CPU and Beats Audio |first=Amar |last=Toor |date=September 14, 2011 |publisher=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=January 13, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106164941/http://www.engadget.com/2011/09/14/htc-sensation-xe-gets-official-packing-1-5ghz-dual-core-cpu-and |archivedate=January 6, 2012 }}</ref> The software was to be included in most new HTC devices, such as the [[HTC One series|One series]].<ref name=\"PCMAG unveiling\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2400755,00.asp |title=Hands On With the HTC One X, S, and One V |magazine=PC Magazine |date=February 26, 2012 |accessdate=February 26, 2012 |author=Segan, Sascha |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120227014223/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0%2C2817%2C2400755%2C00.asp |archivedate=February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"Tech Crunch Unveiling\">{{cite news |url= https://techcrunch.com/2012/09/19/htc-8x-windows-phon |title=HTC Officially Reveals The 8X: 4.3-Inch 720p Display, 1.5GHz Dual-Core Processor, Beats Audio |work=TechCrunch |date=September 19, 2012 |accessdate=September 19, 2012 |last=Velazco |first=Chris |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920093127/http://techcrunch.com/2012/09/19/htc-8x-windows-phon/ |archivedate= September 20, 2012 }}</ref> The Sensation XE and Rezound were also bundled with Beats by Dre earbuds, but HTC abandoned the practice on future devices. A HTC product executive claimed that despite the prominence of the Beats brand, \"an accessory like the headphone doesn't factor in when someone is buying a smartphone\".<ref name=cnet-noearphones>{{cite web|title= More HTC handsets with Beats headphones? Probably not|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-57410616-94/more-htc-handsets-with-beats-headphones-probably-not/|website=CNET|accessdate=22 April 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130407154409/http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-57410616-94/more-htc-handsets-with-beats-headphones-probably-not/|archivedate=7 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Car audio ====\nIn 2011, Beats reached a deal with [[Chrysler LLC]] to feature Beats-branded [[Vehicle audio|audio systems]] in its vehicles. The first vehicle under the partnership was its [[Chrysler 300#Second generation|2012 Chrysler 300S]] [[luxury vehicle]], which included a 10-speaker ''Beats by Dr. Dre'' sound system.<ref name=bloomberg-htcbeats /><ref name=\"forbes-french\">{{cite magazine|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/worldviews/2012/02/27/meet-the-boss-behind-chryslers-image-makeover-he-is-french/|title=Meet The Boss Behind Chrysler's Image Makeover; He Is French|magazine=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=2012-03-20 |first=Nicole |last=Kekeh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319095800/http://www.forbes.com/sites/worldviews/2012/02/27/meet-the-boss-behind-chryslers-image-makeover-he-is-french/|archivedate=2012-03-19}}</ref> Beats audio systems have also been included in models from [[Fiat Chrysler Automobiles]]' other marques. Automobile brands that currently have Beats audio systems available in its vehicles are [[Dodge]], [[Chrysler (brand)|Chrysler]], [[Jeep]], [[Fiat]], [[Volkswagen]], and [[SEAT]].<ref>https://www.beatsbydre.com/beats-audio</ref>\n\n=== Beats Music ===\n{{Main|Beats Music}}\nOn July 2, 2012, Beats announced it had acquired the [[online music]] service [[MOG (online music)|MOG]], in a purchase reported to have been between $10 million and $16 million. Beats stated that the acquisition was part of the company's goal to develop a \"truly end-to-end music experience\". The acquisition did not include the company's blog and advertising network, the MOG Music Network,<ref name=usatoday-mogbeats>{{cite news|title=Beats Electronics acquires MOG music service|url= http://content.usatoday.com/communities/technologylive/post/2012/07/beats-electronics-accquires-mog-music-service/1|accessdate=13 October 2012|newspaper=USA Today|date=2 July 2012|first=Mike |last=Snider |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121206002655/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/technologylive/post/2012/07/beats-electronics-accquires-mog-music-service/1|archivedate=6 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=adw-beats>{{cite web|title=Beats Electronics Acquires Mog Rapper Dr. Dre's headphone makers scoop up digital streaming service|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/technology/beats-electronics-acquires-mog-141575|work=Adweek|publisher=Adweek|accessdate=13 October 2012|author=Charlie Warzel|date=2 July 2012 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023081812/http://www.adweek.com/news/technology/beats-electronics-acquires-mog-141575|archivedate=23 October 2012}}</ref> which was sold in a separate transaction to the broadcasting company [[Townsquare Media]] in August 2012.<ref name=townsquare-mog>{{cite web|title=Remaining half of Mog Music Network sells to Townsquare Media Group|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/remaining-half-of-mog-music-network-sells-to-townsquare-media-group/051510|work=MusicWeek|publisher=Intent Media|accessdate=13 October 2012|author=Rhian Jones|date=24 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309210640/http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/remaining-half-of-mog-music-network-sells-to-townsquare-media-group/051510|archivedate=9 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhile MOG indicated that it would continue to operate independently with no immediate change in service,<ref name=adw-beats /> Beats subsequently announced a new subscription-based online music service, known as [[Beats Music]], which launched in January 2014. In comparison to its competitors, such as [[Spotify]] and [[Google Play Music]], the service emphasizes recommendations by music professionals alongside algorithmic recommendations.<ref name=verge-beatsmusicannounce>{{cite web|title=Beats Music arrives January 21st, family plan exclusive to AT&T customers|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/11/5298562/beats-music-arrives-january-21st-family-plan-exclusive-to-at-t|work=The Verge|accessdate=12 January 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140112063821/http://www.theverge.com/2014/1/11/5298562/beats-music-arrives-january-21st-family-plan-exclusive-to-at-t|archivedate=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=billboard-beatsmusic>{{cite web|title=Beats Music Beefs Up Curation Team, Says Service Is 'Coming Soon'|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/digital-and-mobile/5645363/beats-music-beefs-up-curation-team-says-service-is|work=Billboard.biz|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130828103929/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/digital-and-mobile/5645363/beats-music-beefs-up-curation-team-says-service-is|archivedate=28 August 2013}}</ref> MOG was shut down on May 31, 2014, and existing users were directed to Beats Music.<ref name=verge-mogshutdown>{{cite web|title=MOG streaming music service shut down |url= https://www.theverge.com/2014/6/1/5770370/mog-streaming-music-service-shut-down|website=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=17 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140815173250/http://www.theverge.com/2014/6/1/5770370/mog-streaming-music-service-shut-down |archivedate= 15 August 2014 }}</ref> Beats Music was in turn replaced by [[Apple Music]] in June 2015; the service also incorporates a Beats-branded online radio station, [[Beats 1]].<ref name=\"NYT WWDC\"/><ref name=tc-beatsdiscontinued/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nSome critics claim that Beats products emphasize appearance over quality and function, arguing that more durable and better-sounding products are available for the same price or lower.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2013/05/are-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-worth-the-money/index.htm |title= Are Beats by Dr. Dre headphones worth the money? |work= consumerreports.org |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131204230212/http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2013/05/are-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-worth-the-money/index.htm|archivedate=2013-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/are-beats-headphones-really-designed-to-trick-you-1715413621|title=Are Beats Headphones Really Designed To Trick You?|first=Mario |last=Aguilar|publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |work=[[Gizmodo]] |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711063936/http://gizmodo.com/are-beats-headphones-really-designed-to-trick-you-1715413621|archivedate=2015-07-11}}</ref> Tests done on an HTC smartphone with Beats Audio indicated that the audio technology is a combination of [[Equalization (audio)|audio equalization]] that boosts the low (bass) and high ends of the audio range,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imgur.com/a/MV0pW|title=What Beats Audio actually does |publisher=Imgur|accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141006142041/http://imgur.com/a/MV0pW|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref> [[Dynamic range compression|audio compression]], and [[Audio power amplifier|audio amplification]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.engadget.com/2011/10/13/htc-sensation-xe-with-beats-audio-review/|title=HTC Sensation XE with Beats Audio review |first=Sharif |last=Sakr|publisher=[[AOL]]|work=[[Engadget]]|accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150222091408/http://www.engadget.com/2011/10/13/htc-sensation-xe-with-beats-audio-review/ |archivedate=22 February 2015}}</ref> On accusations that Beats' products were \"bass heavy\", Beats current president denies it, citing that their products are not for reference, but rather for playback.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/28287697|title=Beats by Dre president defends headphone bass quality|publisher=BBC Newsbeat |accessdate= 7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150219203409/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/28287697|archivedate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Apple}}\n{{Dr. Dre}}\n\n[[Category:2006 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2006 in technology]]\n[[Category:2010s fashion]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Culver City, California]]\n[[Category:Dr. Dre]]\n[[Category:Audio equipment manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Headphones]]\n[[Category:Headphones manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2008]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:2010 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:2014 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Beats Electronics LLC\n| logo = [[File:Beats Electronics logo.svg|110px]]\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| founders = [[Dr. Dre]]<br />[[Jimmy Iovine]]\n| area_served = [[World]]wide\n| key_people = [[Luke Wood]] (President)<br />Matthew Costello (COO)<ref name=\"Inc\">{{cite web|title=What Beats' President Said About Expansion--Before Apple Bought It For $14 Pesos|url=http://www.inc.com/burt-helm/apple-buys-beats.html?cid=em01011week22day28a |work=[[Inc.com]]|publisher=Mansueto Ventures|accessdate=31 May 2014|first=Burt |last=Helm|date=28 May 2014}}</ref><br />[[will.i.am]] (partner)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/digital-and-mobile/6106526/beats-by-william-co-founding-and-cashing-in-with-jimmy|title=Beats By will.i.am: Co-Founding and Cashing In With Jimmy Iovine |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150415043755/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/digital-and-mobile/6106526/beats-by-william-co-founding-and-cashing-in-with-jimmy |archivedate= 2015-04-15 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><br />[[Noel Lee (executive)|Noel Lee]] (Investor)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/5981823/beat-by-dre-the-inside-story-of-how-monster-lost-the-world|title=Beat By Dre: The Exclusive Inside Story of How Monster Lost the World|first=Sam |last=Biddle|publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |work=[[Gizmodo]] |accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150110105523/http://gizmodo.com/5981823/beat-by-dre-the-inside-story-of-how-monster-lost-the-world|archivedate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n| industry = {{flatlist|\n*[[Sound recording and reproduction|Audio]]\n*[[Consumer electronics]]\n}}\n| products = {{flatlist|\n*[[Headphones]]\n*[[Bluetooth]]-enabled accessories\n*[[Loudspeaker|Speakers]]\n}}\n| revenue = [[US$]]1.5 billion (2013)<ref>{{cite news |last=Ong |first=Janet |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/12/arts/music/beats-music-enters-online-streaming-market.html |title=Algorithm for Your Personal Rhythm |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2014-01-14 |accessdate=2014-05-09 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140510182731/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/12/arts/music/beats-music-enters-online-streaming-market.html |archivedate=2014-05-10 }}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 700 ({{As of|2014}})\n| parent = [[HTC]] (2010-2014) (partial ownership)<br />\n[[Apple Inc.]] (2014\u2013present)\n| subsid = \n| vector_logo = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|2006}}\n| location_city = [[Culver City, California]], [[United States]]\n| origins = \n| homepage = [https://www.beatsbydre.com/ www.beatsbydre.com]\n}}\n'''Beats Electronics LLC''' (also known as '''Beats by Dr. Dre''', or simply '''Beats by Dre''') is a subsidiary of [[Apple Inc.]] that produces [[Sound recording and reproduction|audio]] products. Headquartered in [[Culver City, California]],<ref name=\"beatsbydre\">{{cite web |url=http://th.beatsbydre.com/on/demandware.store/Sites-beats-Intl-Site/th_TH/CustomerService-Company |title=About us section |accessdate=2013-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131227014659/http://th.beatsbydre.com/on/demandware.store/Sites-beats-Intl-Site/th_TH/CustomerService-Company |archivedate=2013-12-27 |df= dmy-all |website=beatsbydre.com }}</ref>{{third-party-inline|date=May 2014}} the company was founded by music producer and rapper [[Dr. Dre]] and [[Interscope Records]] co-founder<ref>Beats Electronics</ref>{{full citation needed|date=October 2018}} [[Jimmy Iovine]].\n\nThe subsidiary's product line is \nprimarily focused on [[headphones]] and [[loudspeaker|speakers]]. The company's original product line was manufactured in partnership with the AV equipment company [[Monster Cable Products]]. Following the end of its contract with the company, Beats took further development of its products in-house. In 2014, the company expanded into the online music market with the launch of a subscription-based streaming service, [[Beats Music]].\n\nIn 2011, [[NPD Group]] reported that Beats' market share was 64% in the U.S. for headphones priced higher than $100, and the brand was valued at $1 billion in September 2013.<ref name=guardian-carlylebillion>{{cite web|title=Dr Dre Beats valued at more than $1bn following Carlyle deal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/27/dr-dre-beats-1bn-carlyle-sale|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140516232041/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/27/dr-dre-beats-1bn-carlyle-sale |archivedate= 16 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=theage-bass />\n\nFor a period, the company was majority-owned by [[Taiwan]]ese [[smartphone]] maker [[HTC]]. The company reduced its stake to 25% in 2012, and sold its remaining stake back to the company in 2013. Concurrently, [[Carlyle Group]] replaced HTC as a minority shareholder, alongside Dr. Dre and Iovine in late 2013. On August 1, 2014, [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] acquired Beats for $3 billion in a cash and stock deal, the largest acquisition in Apple's history.\n\n== History ==\n=== Formation ===\n[[File:Dr. Dre at Coachella 2012 cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Dr. Dre]] (seen in 2012), company co-founder]]\n[[File:Jimmy Iovine & David Guetta.jpg|thumb|Jimmy Iovine and David Guetta]]\nThe company was formally established in 2006,<ref name=beatscrunch>{{cite web|title=Beats Electronics |url= http://www.crunchbase.com/organization/beats-by-dr-dre|work=CrunchBase|publisher=CrunchBase.com|accessdate=20 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521045821/http://www.crunchbase.com/organization/beats-by-dr-dre|archivedate=21 May 2014 }}</ref> a time when Iovine perceived two key problems in the music industry: the impact of [[Copyright infringement|piracy]] on music sales and the substandard audio quality provided by [[Apple, Inc.|Apple]]'s plastic earbuds. Iovine later recalled that Dre said to him: \"Man, it's one thing that people steal my music. It's another thing to destroy the feeling of what I've worked on.\" Iovine sought the opinions of musicians with \"great taste\", such as [[M.I.A. (rapper)|M.I.A.]], [[Pharrell Williams]], [[will.i.am]], and [[Gwen Stefani]] during the early developmental stage.<ref name=\"Burt\" /> Beats initially partnered with [[Monster Cable Products|Monster Cable]], an audio and video component manufacturer based in [[Brisbane, California]], to manufacture and develop the first Beats-branded products, and debuted its first product, ''Beats by Dr. Dre Studio'' headphones, on July 25, 2008.\n\nTo promote its products, Beats primarily relied on endorsements by [[pop music|pop]] and [[hip-hop music|hip-hop]] music performers, including [[product placement]] within [[music video]]s, and partnering with musicians and other celebrities to develop [[celebrity branding|co-branded]] products.<ref name=\"Burt\">{{cite web|title=How Dr. Dre's Headphones Company Became a Billion-Dollar Business|url=http://www.inc.com/audacious-companies/burt-helm/beats.html|work=[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]|publisher=Mansueto Ventures|accessdate=31 May 2014|author=Burt Helm|date=May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"bw-beats\">{{cite news |title=Beats Electronics Is Breaking Up with Monster |author=Cliff Edwards |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/beats-electronics-is-breaking-up-with-monster-01122012.html?campaign_id=rss_null |newspaper=[[Business Week]] |date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=13 January 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116122935/http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/beats-electronics-is-breaking-up-with-monster-01122012.html?campaign_id=rss_null |archivedate=16 January 2012 }}</ref><ref name=bbc-headphones>{{cite news|title=From Lemmy to Snooki, celebs are desperate to sell you headphones|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20970495|work=BBC|accessdate=27 August 2013|date=10 January 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130925052740/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20970495|archivedate=25 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=time-beats>{{cite news|title=How Dr. Dre Made $300 Headphones a Must-Have Accessory |url= http://business.time.com/2013/01/16/how-dr-dre-made-300-headphones-a-must-have-accessory/ |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate= 27 August 2013 |date= 16 January 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130824225748/http://business.time.com/2013/01/16/how-dr-dre-made-300-headphones-a-must-have-accessory/ |archivedate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Beats' use of endorsements by musicians helped the company aggressively target the [[Young adult (psychology)|young adult]] demographics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fields|first=Brandi|year=2014|title=Selling the Beat: Hip-Hop Culture and Product Branding Among Young Adults|url=http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1666&context=gs_rp |journal=[[Southern Illinois University]] |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160704041240/http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1666&context=gs_rp |archivedate= 2016-07-04 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== HTC purchase and non-renewal of Monster contract ===\nIn August 2010, mobile phone manufacturer HTC acquired a 50.1% majority share in Beats for $309 million. The purchase was intended to allow HTC to compete with other cellphone makers by associating themselves with the Beats brand,<ref name=md-htcsell /> as the purchase also granted HTC exclusive rights to manufacture smartphones with Beats-branded audio systems.<ref name=cnet-htc>{{cite web|last=Sandoval|first=Greg|title=HTC to acquire majority stake in Dr. Dre's Beats|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-31001_3-20090967-261/htc-to-acquire-majority-stake-in-dr-dres-beats/|publisher=[[CNET]]|accessdate=20 March 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120504072603/http://news.cnet.com/8301-31001_3-20090967-261/htc-to-acquire-majority-stake-in-dr-dres-beats/|archivedate=4 May 2012}}</ref> Despite its majority acquisition, HTC allowed Beats to operate as an autonomous company.<ref name=cnet-htc /> [[Luke Wood]], President of Beats in May 2014, joined the company in January 2010, when the company was a \"licensing business\". Wood had previously worked under Iovine at Interscope Records.<ref name=\"Inc\" />\n\nOn January 19, 2012, ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' reported that Beats and Monster would not renew their production contract and their partnership ceased at the end of 2012. Dre and Iovine subsequently decided to oversee the entire operation of the company, from manufacturing to R&D,<ref name=\"Inc\" /> and aimed to double its workforce to around 300 employees. Monster would ultimately begin marketing its own competing line of premium headphones aimed towards an older demographic.<ref name=\"bw-beats\" /> At the time, neither Dre, Iovine or Wood were experienced in the operation of a company at such a grand level, but Wood explained in 2014:<blockquote>I didn't have manufacturing experience, but I had experience of building something from scratch \u2026 Every time we put out an album, it was basically like building a new business--a unique cast of characters, unique challenges and opportunities, and trying to figure out a unique path to market.<ref name=\"Inc\" /></blockquote>\n\nIn October 2012, Beats unveiled its first two self-developed products, \"Beats Executive\" headphones and \"[[Beats Pill]]\" wireless speakers\u2014Iovine believed that the company would now have to \"control [its] own destiny\" in order to continue its growth. Iovine also commented on how other headphone makers had attempted to emulate Beats' celebrity endorsement business model (including Monster themselves, who unveiled [[Earth, Wind and Fire]] and [[Miles Davis]]-themed headphones at the 2012 [[Consumer Electronics Show]]),<ref name=\"bw-beats\" /> stating that \"some of our competitors are cheap engineers who have never been to a recording studio. You can't just stick someone's name on a headphone that doesn't know anything about sound.\"<ref name=\"bw-beats\" /><ref name=billboard-destiny>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Iovine on Beats by Dre Parting With Monster: 'We Have to Control Our Own Destiny' |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/511582/jimmy-iovine-on-beats-by-dre-parting-with-monster-we-have-to-control-our-own |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130817062349/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/511582/jimmy-iovine-on-beats-by-dre-parting-with-monster-we-have-to-control-our-own|archivedate=17 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=billboard-firstinhouse>{{cite web|title=Beats By Dre Debuts First Post-Monster Cable Products|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1083371/beats-by-dre-debuts-first-post-monster-cable-products|work=Billboard|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130905221257/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1083371/beats-by-dre-debuts-first-post-monster-cable-products |archivedate=5 September 2013}}</ref> Following the decision to transform Beats into an autonomous entity, the company's revenues reached the $1 billion mark, according to Iovine.<ref name=\"Inc\" />\n\n=== HTC sale and Beats Music ===\n[[File:Beats Music logo.svg|200px|alt=The logo that Beats Music, a subsidiary of Beats Electronics, uses.|thumb|The logo for Beats Music.]]\nIn July 2012, HTC sold back half of its stake in Beats for $150 million, remaining the largest shareholder with 25.1 percent.<ref>{{cite news|title=HTC Just Sold Back Half Of Its Holdings In Beats Electronics|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/htc-just-sold-back-half-oin-beats-electronics-2012-7|accessdate=21 November 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=24 July 2012|author=Jonathan Standing & Clare Jim|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209044953/http://www.businessinsider.com/htc-just-sold-back-half-of-its-holdings-in-beats-electronics-2012-7|archivedate=9 December 2012}}</ref> The sale was intended to provide \"flexibility for global expansion while maintaining HTC's major stake and commercial exclusivity in mobile\".<ref name=md-htcsell>{{cite news|title=After HTC Sale, Dr. Dre and Jimmy Iovine Gain Control of Beats Headphones |url= http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/after-htc-sale-dr-dre-and-jimmy-iovine-gain-control-of-beats-headphones/ |work= Media Decoder|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=26 July 2012|first=Ben|last=Sisario|date=23 July 2012 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120726003018/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/after-htc-sale-dr-dre-and-jimmy-iovine-gain-control-of-beats-headphones/|archivedate=26 July 2012}}</ref> In August 2013, reports surfaced that Beats' founders planned to buy back HTC's remaining minority stake in the company, and pursue a new, unspecified partner for a future investment.<ref name=guardian-beatshtcout>{{cite web|title=Dr Dre's Beats to pull plug on HTC in favour of new business partner |url= https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/aug/19/dr-dre-beats-htc-new-partner|work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status= live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821145755/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/aug/19/dr-dre-beats-htc-new-partner|archivedate=21 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=bloomberg-htcbeats>{{cite web|title=Straight Outta HTC: Beats Audio May Have a New Solo Project|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-08-20/straight-outta-htc-beats-audio-may-have-a-new-solo-project|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130823071842/http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-08-20/straight-outta-htc-beats-audio-may-have-a-new-solo-project|archivedate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2013, HTC confirmed that it would sell its remaining 24.84% stake in Beats back to the company for $265 million. Concurrently, Beats announced that the [[Carlyle Group]] would make a $500 million minority investment in the company.<ref name=wsj-carayleears /><ref>{{cite news|title=HTC to Sell Back Stake in Beats Electronics for $265 Million |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-27/htc-to-sell-back-stake-in-beats-headphone-maker-for-265-million.html|accessdate=29 September 2013|newspaper=[[Bloomberg LP]]|date=27 September 2013|first=Yu-Huay |last=Sun|first2=Edmond |last2=Lococo |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130929145907/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-27/htc-to-sell-back-stake-in-beats-headphone-maker-for-265-million.html|archivedate=29 September 2013}}</ref> The overall deal valued Beats Electronics at $1 billion<ref name=guardian-carlylebillion /> and helped HTC turn a [[net profit]] of $10.3 million for the fourth quarter of 2013, following HTC's first quarterly loss in company history.<ref name=verge-beatssaleprofit>{{cite web|title=HTC narrowly avoids second quarterly loss by selling Beats stake|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/5/5275894/htc-narrowly-avoids-second-quarterly-loss-by-selling-beats-stake|work=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=24 January 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140124014911/http://www.theverge.com/2014/1/5/5275894/htc-narrowly-avoids-second-quarterly-loss-by-selling-beats-stake|archivedate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe appointment of a new [[chief operating officer]] (COO), a role previously filled by Wood,<ref name=\"Inc\" /> was announced in early November 2013. Matthew Costello, formerly of [[IKEA]] and HTC, was formally appointed to the role in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beats Electronics Names COO|url=http://www.labusinessjournal.com/news/2013/nov/06/beats-electronics-names-coo/|work=[[Los Angeles Business Journal]] |accessdate=8 November 2013|first=Natalie |last=Jarvey|date=6 November 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503115233/http://www.labusinessjournal.com/news/2013/nov/06/beats-electronics-names-coo/ |archivedate= 3 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=134391936&privcapId=65358694&previousCapId=65358694&previousTitle=Beats%20Electronics,%20LLC|title=Executive Profile Matthew Vincent Costello|last=|first=|date=31 May 2014|work=Bloomberg Businesweek|publisher=[[Bloomberg LP]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 21, 2014, the company launched Beats Music, a subscription-based online music streaming service.<ref name=verge-beatsmusicannounce /> Prior to the launch of the service, Beats stated that it intends to provide a different type of streaming experience to what was available on the market at the time. Additionally, the service would only be available to consumers in the U.S. at inception.<ref name=\"Gate\">{{cite web|title=Beats Music reveals launch details|url=http://www.commercegate.com/beats-music-reveals-launch-details/|work=CommerceGate|publisher=CommerceGate Ireland Ltd|accessdate=31 May 2014|date=23 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531162219/http://www.commercegate.com/beats-music-reveals-launch-details/|archivedate=31 May 2014}}</ref> Chief executive of Beats at the time, Ian Rogers, said:<blockquote>We wanted to build a music service that combined the freedom of an on-demand subscription service\u2014unlimited, uninterrupted streaming and downloads of tens of millions of songs \u2013 but layer on top features that would give you that feeling only music that moves you can give. The right song at the right time will give you a chill. Make you pull someone close. Nod your head. Sing in the mirror. Roll down the car window and crank the volume to the right.<ref name=\"Gate\" /></blockquote>\n\n=== Subsidiary of Apple Inc. (2014\u2013present) ===\nOn May 8, 2014, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] was in negotiations with Beats to purchase the company for $3.2 billion\u2014the largest purchase in Apple's history, ahead of its $429 million purchase of [[NeXT]] in 1996.<ref name=cnet-beatsapple>{{cite news|title=Apple said to be in talks to buy Beats Electronics for $3.2B |url= https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-said-to-be-in-talks-to-buy-beats-electronics-for-3-2b/|accessdate=9 May 2014|newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=9 May 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510134236/http://www.cnet.com/news/apple-said-to-be-in-talks-to-buy-beats-electronics-for-3-2b/|archivedate=10 May 2014}}</ref> The impending deal was prematurely and indirectly revealed in a photo and [[YouTube]] video posted to [[Facebook]] by [[Tyrese Gibson]] on May 8, 2014; the video documented a celebration in which Gibson and Dr. Dre made boasting remarks about the acquisition, with Dre declaring himself the \"first billionaire in hip hop\", while Gibson declared that the \"[[The World's Billionaires|Forbes list]]\" had changed. Both the photo and video were removed from Facebook the following morning, but both remain on Gibson's YouTube channel.<ref name=\"Inc\" /><ref name=cnet-tyrese>{{cite web|title='First billionaire in hip-hop' Dre boasts of Apple-Beats deal on Facebook |url= https://www.cnet.com/news/first-billionaire-in-hip-hop-dre-boasts-of-apple-beats-deal-on-facebook/|work=[[CNET]]|accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509132648/http://www.cnet.com/news/first-billionaire-in-hip-hop-dre-boasts-of-apple-beats-deal-on-facebook/|archivedate=9 May 2014}}</ref> Indeed, analysts estimated that the rumored deal would make Dr. Dre the first billionaire in the hip-hop music industry in terms of [[net worth]], assuming that he held at least 15% ownership in the company prior to the deal. Dr. Dre was listed with a net worth of $550 million on [[Forbes]]' ''[[The World's Billionaires]]'' 2014 list. It was also estimated that the [[Carlyle Group]] would receive a profit of $1 billion from the sale of its minority stake in the company.<ref name=wsj-carayleears>{{cite web|title=Apple's Beats Deal Is Music to Carlyle's Ears |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2014/05/08/apples-beats-deal-is-music-to-carlyles-ears/|work=MoneyBeat|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140509015946/https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2014/05/08/apples-beats-deal-is-music-to-carlyles-ears/ |archivedate=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=independent-drerichest>{{cite web|title=If Apple buys Beats Electronics for $3.2bn, will Dr Dre become hip hop's first billionaire?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/if-apple-buys-beats-electronics-for-32bn-will-dr-dre-become-hip-hops-first-billionaire-9343973.html|work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status= live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509145255/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/if-apple-buys-beats-electronics-for-32bn-will-dr-dre-become-hip-hops-first-billionaire-9343973.html|archivedate=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=wsj-drerichest>{{cite web|title=Could an Apple Beats Acquisition Make Dr. Dre the First Rap Billionaire?|url= https://blogs.wsj.com/corporate-intelligence/2014/05/08/will-apples-beats-deal-make-dr-dre-the-first-rap-billionaire/ |work=Corporate Intelligence|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140511214002/https://blogs.wsj.com/corporate-intelligence/2014/05/08/will-apples-beats-deal-make-dr-dre-the-first-rap-billionaire/|archivedate=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2014, Apple officially announced its intention to acquire Beats Electronics for $3 billion\u2014with $400 million to be paid in Apple stock and the remainder in cash. Some reports suggested that the reduction in value may have been a result of lower-than-expected subscriber numbers for the Beats Music service.<ref name=\"Inc\" /> Iovine felt that Beats had always \"belonged\" with Apple, as the company modeled itself after Apple's \"unmatched ability to marry culture and technology\". In regard to the deal, Apple CEO [[Tim Cook]] stated that \"Music is such an important part of all of our lives and holds a special place within our hearts at Apple. That's why we have kept investing in music and are bringing together these extraordinary teams so we can continue to create the most innovative music products and services in the world.\" Beyond stocking Beats products at its [[Apple Store|retail outlets]], Apple did not provide any further indications over how Beats would be integrated into its product line at the time, and whether Beats Music, which competed with Apple's own [[iTunes Radio]] service, would continue to operate after the acquisition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/05/28/apple-acquires-beats-electronics-for-3-billion/ |title=Apple acquires Beats Electronics for $3 billion |work=Engadget |date=May 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529084316/http://www.engadget.com/2014/05/28/apple-acquires-beats-electronics-for-3-billion/ |archivedate=May 29, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=verge-beatsappleconfirmed>{{cite web|title=Apple confirms it's buying Beats for $3 billion|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/5/28/5700530/apple-confirms-beats-acquisition|work=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=28 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140529051629/http://www.theverge.com/2014/5/28/5700530/apple-confirms-beats-acquisition |archivedate= 29 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=apple-pr>{{cite web|title=Apple to Acquire Beats Music & Beats Electronics |url= https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2014/05/28Apple-to-Acquire-Beats-Music-Beats-Electronics.html |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |accessdate= 28 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140528210544/http://www.apple.com/pr/library/2014/05/28Apple-to-Acquire-Beats-Music-Beats-Electronics.html |archivedate= 28 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe acquisition closed on August 1, 2014. To eliminate redundancy, Apple planned to lay off 200 workers from Beats' workforce of around 700.<ref name=OfficialClose>{{cite web|title=Apple closes $3B Beats deal, welcomes the company 'to the family' |url= https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-closes-3b-beats-deal-welcomes-the-company-to-the-family/|website=[[CNET]]|accessdate=1 August 2014 |url-status= live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802130730/http://www.cnet.com/news/apple-closes-3b-beats-deal-welcomes-the-company-to-the-family/|archivedate=2 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=bloomberg-jobcuts>{{cite web|title=Apple Said to Target 200 Job Cuts at Beats After Deal|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-07-30/apple-said-to-cut-200-jobs-at-beats-after-acquisition.html |website=[[Bloomberg LP]] |accessdate=1 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140801010755/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-07-30/apple-said-to-cut-200-jobs-at-beats-after-acquisition.html |archivedate=1 August 2014}}</ref> Beats Music was discontinued effective with the launch of [[Apple Music]] on June 30, 2015.<ref name=\"NYT WWDC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/apple-wwdc-2015/apple-music-does-everything-apple-says/ |accessdate=June 21, 2015 |title=Apple W.W.D.C. 2015: iOS 9, Apple Pay and Other Announcements |date= June 8, 2015 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150622124220/http://www.nytimes.com/live/apple-wwdc-2015/apple-music-does-everything-apple-says/ |archivedate=June 22, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=tc-beatsdiscontinued>{{cite web|title=Beats Music Tells Users To Switch To Apple Music|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/08/beat-it/|website=TechCrunch|publisher=AOL Inc. (Verizon Communications)|accessdate=3 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703164647/http://techcrunch.com/2015/06/08/beat-it/|archivedate=3 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Bose lawsuit ===\nIn July 2014, [[Bose Corporation]] sued Beats Electronics, alleging that its \"Studio\" line incorporated [[noise cancellation]] technology that [[patent infringement|infringed]] five patents held by the company. Bose has also sought an injunction which would ban the infringing products from being imported or sold in the United States.<ref name=time-beatslawsuit>{{cite web|title=Bose Is Suing Beats Over Headphone Patents|url=http://time.com/3036763/bose-beats-lawsuit/|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|accessdate=1 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140803015449/http://time.com/3036763/bose-beats-lawsuit/ |archivedate=3 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=wsj-soundoff>{{cite web|title=Sound Off: Bose Sues Beats Over Noise-Cancelling Patents |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/07/25/sound-off-bose-sues-beats-over-noise-cancelling-patents/|website=Digits|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=1 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140729143845/https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/07/25/sound-off-bose-sues-beats-over-noise-cancelling-patents/|archivedate=29 July 2014}}</ref> The lawsuit was settled out of court. Apple pulled all Bose products from its retail outlets, although it is unclear whether it was in response to the lawsuit, an [[ambush marketing]] conflict involving Beats and the [[NFL]] (which had recently named Bose as one of its official sponsors, and thus fined a player for displaying the Beats logo during an official activity), or as a result of Apple's acquisition of Beats.<ref name=verge-boseremoved>{{cite news|title=Apple has removed all Bose products from its store|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/10/17/6995403/apple-removes-bose-products-from-store |accessdate=17 October 2014|work=[[The Verge]]|date=17 October 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141018135935/http://www.theverge.com/2014/10/17/6995403/apple-removes-bose-products-from-store |archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref> However, two months later, Bose products returned to the shelves of Apple Stores. The companies settled in October 2014: details were not disclosed.<ref name=cnet-bosesettled>{{cite web|title=Apple's Beats, Bose settle patent spat over noise-canceling tech|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apples-beats-bose-settle-patent-spat-over-noise-canceling-tech/ |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150108005933/http://www.cnet.com/news/apples-beats-bose-settle-patent-spat-over-noise-canceling-tech/ |archivedate=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Monster lawsuit ===\nIn January 2015, [[Monster Cable|Monster Inc.]] sued Beats for [[fraud]], alleging that the company had used illicit tactics to force Monster out of the venture whilst retaining rights to the technologies and products that it had co-developed, and engaged in [[collusion]] to harm Monster's own audio products business. Monster argued that the acquisition of Beats by HTC and its founders' subsequent buyback was a \"sham\" to take control of Monster's stake in the company\u2014which could have been valued at over $100 million in the Apple purchase, that the company had \"concealed\" the role of Monster and its CEO [[Noel Lee (executive)|Noel Lee]] in the design and engineering of its products, and that \"had the partnership expired on its own terms, there would have been no transfer of Monster's years of work [onto the company]\". Monster also alleged that Beats had partaken in [[anti-competitive practices]] with retailers to force those offering Beats products to not offer Monster's competing products.<ref name=verge-monsterlawsuit>{{cite web |title= Monster sues Beats and co-founders Dr. Dre and Jimmy Iovine for fraud |url= https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/6/7505639/monster-suing-beats-and-co-founders-dr-dre-and-jimmy-iovine |website=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150107075249/http://www.theverge.com/2015/1/6/7505639/monster-suing-beats-and-co-founders-dr-dre-and-jimmy-iovine |archivedate=7 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=usatoday-monsterlawsuit>{{cite web|title=Tech firm Monster sues Beats and founders Dre and Iovine|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/01/06/monster-suit-beats-electronics/21355033/|website=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150107053857/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/01/06/monster-suit-beats-electronics/21355033/ |archivedate=7 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Beatrayed by Dre? Noel Lee says he built the headphones Apple paid $3 billion for. His take? $0. Now he's suing for his share.|work=[[Bloomberg LP]]|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2015-06-22/beatrayed-by-dre-|date=22 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160712212651/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2015-06-22/beatrayed-by-dre-|archivedate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that in retaliation for the lawsuit, Apple Inc. revoked Monster's membership in the [[MFi Program]] on May 5, 2015, meaning that Monster can no longer manufacture licensed accessories for [[iPhone]], [[iPod]] and [[iPad]] products, and must cease the sale of existing licensed products that contain the certification or technology licensed through the program by September 2015.<ref name=wsj-monsterrevoked>{{cite news|title=Apple Revokes Monster's Authority to Make Licensed Accessories|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-revokes-monsters-authority-to-make-licensed-accessories-1434481512 |accessdate=17 June 2015|work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150617004548/http://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-revokes-monsters-authority-to-make-licensed-accessories-1434481512 |archivedate=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe case was dismissed in August 2016, with a Supreme Court ruling that Beats \"had the right to terminate the agreement as of January 7th, 2013 or when there was a transaction resulting in a change of control of Beats\", and that Monster \"did not obtain the right to approve the change of control. Nor did the agreement require that any change of control had to be objectively reasonable\".<ref name=\"verge-monsterthrownout\">{{cite web|title=Monster's lawsuit against Beats has gone very poorly |url= https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/30/12719232/monster-beats-lawsuit-claims-dismissed-apple|website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=26 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161225171352/http://www.theverge.com/2016/8/30/12719232/monster-beats-lawsuit-claims-dismissed-apple |archivedate=25 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\n[[File:BeatsHeadphones-2 (47705430872).jpg|thumb|right|Example of Beats Headphones]]\nBeats' original product line were ''Beats by Dre'' headphones. In promotional materials, Dre outlined the line's advantages by alleging that listeners were not able to hear \"all\" of the music with most headphones, and that Beats would allow people to \"hear what the artists hear, and listen to the music the way they should: the way I do\". In comparison to most headphones, ''Beats'' products were characterized by an emphasis towards producing larger amounts of [[bass (music)|bass]], and are particularly optimized towards [[hip-hop music|hip-hop]] and [[pop music]].<ref name=theage-bass>{{cite news|title=How Beats by Dre knocked out better headphones|url=http://www.theage.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/how-beats-by-dre-knocked-out-better-headphones-20130913-2tola.html|work=The Age|accessdate=29 November 2013|location=Melbourne|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131120060243/http://www.theage.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/how-beats-by-dre-knocked-out-better-headphones-20130913-2tola.html|archivedate=20 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=cr-arebeatsworthit>{{cite web|title=Are Beats by Dr. Dre headphones worth the money?|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2013/05/are-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-worth-the-money/index.htm|publisher=Consumer Reports|accessdate=29 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204230212/http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2013/05/are-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-worth-the-money/index.htm|archivedate=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=geek-beats>{{cite web|last=Evans|first=Joel|title=Review: Beats by Dr. Dre headphones|url=http://www.geek.com/articles/gadgets/review-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-20080730/|publisher=Geek.com|accessdate=23 May 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428202630/http://www.geek.com/articles/gadgets/review-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-20080730|archivedate=28 April 2012}}</ref> In October 2012, Beats unveiled its first two self-developed products, the Beats Executive noise-cancelling headphones (to compete with similar offerings by [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] and [[Sennheiser]]) and the [[Beats Pill]] portable speaker.<ref name=\"bw-beats\" /><ref name=billboard-firstinhouse /> In October 2015, Beats launched a new collection of speakers including the upgraded Beats Pill+ Speaker.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beats Pill+ Speaker Launches Alongside New Colors for Solo2 Headphones|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2015/10/26/beats-pill-speaker-launches/|accessdate=29 October 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029002146/http://www.macrumors.com/2015/10/26/beats-pill-speaker-launches/|archivedate=29 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Headphones ===\n==== Beats Solo Pro ====\nThis is an on the ear style headphone. Along with the '''Powerbeats Pro''' true-wireless earphones, they are part of a new generation of Beats products made from the ground up with Apple. They are the first on-ear headphones made by Beats to feature [[active noise canceling]]. They are sold alongside the '''Solo 3'''. \n\n==== Beats Solo 3 Wireless ====\nThis is an on the ear style headphone. It can last for 40 hours on a single charge or indefinitely when plugged in via the headphone jack.\n\n==== Beats Studio 3 Wireless ====\nThis is currently the high-end wireless headphones that Beats offers. It connects by Bluetooth and has 40 hours of battery life, with 22 hours of battery life with adaptive noise cancelling on. It features Apple's [[Apple W series|W1 chip]] for quick connection to [[Apple device]]s running [[iOS 10]], [[macOS Sierra]], or [[watchOS 4]] or later. It also features pure adaptive [[noise cancelling technology]] which uses microphones both inside and outside the ear cups to measure sound levels based on the environment. If there is any headgear or eyewear on the user's head it calibrates the noise cancelling and volume level accordingly. It comes in a wide range of colors and editions, including black, blue and special collections such as the [[National Basketball Association|\"NBA]] Collection\".\n\n=== Earbuds ===\nOn September 7, 2016, '''Powerbeats\u00b3''' were released. On February 10, 2017, '''BeatsX''' neckband-style headphones were released.<ref>https://www.cnet.com/reviews/beatsx-earphones-review/</ref> '''[[Powerbeats Pro]]''' were released on May 10, 2019, in the United States and 2 weeks later for UK and Europe.<ref>Cleo Clarkeson, [https://tenpire.com/meet-the-new-beats-powerbeats-pro/ \"Meet The New Beats Powerbeats Pro\"], ''Tenpire'', 10 April 2019.</ref>\n\n=== Beats Audio ===\nThe company has also licensed the Beats brand, under the name ''Beats Audio'' (rendered '''beats audio'''), and technology to other manufacturers. In 2009, [[Hewlett-Packard|HP]] began to offer [[personal computer]]s equipped with ''Beats Audio'' systems, beginning with its [[HP Envy]] line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www8.hp.com/us/en/hp-news/press-release.html?id=169479|title=HP News \u2013 HP and Beats Electronics Set New Premium Standard for Music Audio on Notebooks|work=hp.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402154046/http://www8.hp.com/us/en/hp-news/press-release.html?id=169479|archivedate=2015-04-02}}</ref> The system features a software [[Equalization (audio)|equalizer]] with a preset that HP marketed as being optimized for higher quality sound output.<ref name=\"hp-beats\">{{cite magazine |title=HP Envy 14: Plenty of Power in a Stylish Package |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/203364/hp_envy_14_plenty_of_power_in_a_stylish_package.html |magazine=[[PCWorld (magazine)|PC World]] |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323194853/http://www.pcworld.com/article/203364/hp_envy_14_plenty_of_power_in_a_stylish_package.html |archivedate=2012-03-23 }}</ref> Beats Electronics ceased its partnership with HP following its purchase by Apple Inc.; HP subsequently entered into a similar agreement with [[Bang & Olufsen]].<ref name=\"cnet-bando\">{{cite web|title=HP makes Bang & Olufsen its new audio partner|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/hp-makes-bang-olufsen-its-new-audio-partner/ |website=CNET|accessdate=21 February 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160226074822/http://www.cnet.com/news/hp-makes-bang-olufsen-its-new-audio-partner/|archivedate=26 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing its acquisition of a stake in the company, most new HTC smartphones began to be released with Beats Audio software, beginning with the [[HTC Sensation XE]]/XL with Beats Audio in September 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/09/14/htc-sensation-xe-gets-official-packing-1-5ghz-dual-core-cpu-and |title=HTC Sensation XE gets official, packing 1.5GHz dual-core CPU and Beats Audio |first=Amar |last=Toor |date=September 14, 2011 |publisher=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=January 13, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106164941/http://www.engadget.com/2011/09/14/htc-sensation-xe-gets-official-packing-1-5ghz-dual-core-cpu-and |archivedate=January 6, 2012 }}</ref> The software was to be included in most new HTC devices, such as the [[HTC One series|One series]].<ref name=\"PCMAG unveiling\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2400755,00.asp |title=Hands On With the HTC One X, S, and One V |magazine=PC Magazine |date=February 26, 2012 |accessdate=February 26, 2012 |author=Segan, Sascha |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120227014223/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0%2C2817%2C2400755%2C00.asp |archivedate=February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"Tech Crunch Unveiling\">{{cite news |url= https://techcrunch.com/2012/09/19/htc-8x-windows-phon |title=HTC Officially Reveals The 8X: 4.3-Inch 720p Display, 1.5GHz Dual-Core Processor, Beats Audio |work=TechCrunch |date=September 19, 2012 |accessdate=September 19, 2012 |last=Velazco |first=Chris |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920093127/http://techcrunch.com/2012/09/19/htc-8x-windows-phon/ |archivedate= September 20, 2012 }}</ref> The Sensation XE and Rezound were also bundled with Beats by Dre earbuds, but HTC abandoned the practice on future devices. A HTC product executive claimed that despite the prominence of the Beats brand, \"an accessory like the headphone doesn't factor in when someone is buying a smartphone\".<ref name=cnet-noearphones>{{cite web|title= More HTC handsets with Beats headphones? Probably not|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-57410616-94/more-htc-handsets-with-beats-headphones-probably-not/|website=CNET|accessdate=22 April 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130407154409/http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-57410616-94/more-htc-handsets-with-beats-headphones-probably-not/|archivedate=7 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Car audio ====\nIn 2011, Beats reached a deal with [[Chrysler LLC]] to feature Beats-branded [[Vehicle audio|audio systems]] in its vehicles. The first vehicle under the partnership was its [[Chrysler 300#Second generation|2012 Chrysler 300S]] [[luxury vehicle]], which included a 10-speaker ''Beats by Dr. Dre'' sound system.<ref name=bloomberg-htcbeats /><ref name=\"forbes-french\">{{cite magazine|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/worldviews/2012/02/27/meet-the-boss-behind-chryslers-image-makeover-he-is-french/|title=Meet The Boss Behind Chrysler's Image Makeover; He Is French|magazine=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=2012-03-20 |first=Nicole |last=Kekeh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319095800/http://www.forbes.com/sites/worldviews/2012/02/27/meet-the-boss-behind-chryslers-image-makeover-he-is-french/|archivedate=2012-03-19}}</ref> Beats audio systems have also been included in models from [[Fiat Chrysler Automobiles]]' other marques. Automobile brands that currently have Beats audio systems available in its vehicles are [[Dodge]], [[Chrysler (brand)|Chrysler]], [[Jeep]], [[Fiat]], [[Volkswagen]], and [[SEAT]].<ref>https://www.beatsbydre.com/beats-audio</ref>\n\n=== Beats Music ===\n{{Main|Beats Music}}\nOn July 2, 2012, Beats announced it had acquired the [[online music]] service [[MOG (online music)|MOG]], in a purchase reported to have been between $10 million and $16 million. Beats stated that the acquisition was part of the company's goal to develop a \"truly end-to-end music experience\". The acquisition did not include the company's blog and advertising network, the MOG Music Network,<ref name=usatoday-mogbeats>{{cite news|title=Beats Electronics acquires MOG music service|url= http://content.usatoday.com/communities/technologylive/post/2012/07/beats-electronics-accquires-mog-music-service/1|accessdate=13 October 2012|newspaper=USA Today|date=2 July 2012|first=Mike |last=Snider |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121206002655/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/technologylive/post/2012/07/beats-electronics-accquires-mog-music-service/1|archivedate=6 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=adw-beats>{{cite web|title=Beats Electronics Acquires Mog Rapper Dr. Dre's headphone makers scoop up digital streaming service|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/technology/beats-electronics-acquires-mog-141575|work=Adweek|publisher=Adweek|accessdate=13 October 2012|author=Charlie Warzel|date=2 July 2012 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023081812/http://www.adweek.com/news/technology/beats-electronics-acquires-mog-141575|archivedate=23 October 2012}}</ref> which was sold in a separate transaction to the broadcasting company [[Townsquare Media]] in August 2012.<ref name=townsquare-mog>{{cite web|title=Remaining half of Mog Music Network sells to Townsquare Media Group|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/remaining-half-of-mog-music-network-sells-to-townsquare-media-group/051510|work=MusicWeek|publisher=Intent Media|accessdate=13 October 2012|author=Rhian Jones|date=24 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309210640/http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/remaining-half-of-mog-music-network-sells-to-townsquare-media-group/051510|archivedate=9 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhile MOG indicated that it would continue to operate independently with no immediate change in service,<ref name=adw-beats /> Beats subsequently announced a new subscription-based online music service, known as [[Beats Music]], which launched in January 2014. In comparison to its competitors, such as [[Spotify]] and [[Google Play Music]], the service emphasizes recommendations by music professionals alongside algorithmic recommendations.<ref name=verge-beatsmusicannounce>{{cite web|title=Beats Music arrives January 21st, family plan exclusive to AT&T customers|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/11/5298562/beats-music-arrives-january-21st-family-plan-exclusive-to-at-t|work=The Verge|accessdate=12 January 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140112063821/http://www.theverge.com/2014/1/11/5298562/beats-music-arrives-january-21st-family-plan-exclusive-to-at-t|archivedate=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=billboard-beatsmusic>{{cite web|title=Beats Music Beefs Up Curation Team, Says Service Is 'Coming Soon'|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/digital-and-mobile/5645363/beats-music-beefs-up-curation-team-says-service-is|work=Billboard.biz|accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130828103929/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/digital-and-mobile/5645363/beats-music-beefs-up-curation-team-says-service-is|archivedate=28 August 2013}}</ref> MOG was shut down on May 31, 2014, and existing users were directed to Beats Music.<ref name=verge-mogshutdown>{{cite web|title=MOG streaming music service shut down |url= https://www.theverge.com/2014/6/1/5770370/mog-streaming-music-service-shut-down|website=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=17 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140815173250/http://www.theverge.com/2014/6/1/5770370/mog-streaming-music-service-shut-down |archivedate= 15 August 2014 }}</ref> Beats Music was in turn replaced by [[Apple Music]] in June 2015; the service also incorporates a Beats-branded online radio station, [[Beats 1]].<ref name=\"NYT WWDC\"/><ref name=tc-beatsdiscontinued/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nSome critics claim that Beats products emphasize appearance over quality and function, arguing that more durable and better-sounding products are available for the same price or lower.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2013/05/are-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-worth-the-money/index.htm |title= Are Beats by Dr. Dre headphones worth the money? |work= consumerreports.org |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131204230212/http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2013/05/are-beats-by-dr-dre-headphones-worth-the-money/index.htm|archivedate=2013-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/are-beats-headphones-really-designed-to-trick-you-1715413621|title=Are Beats Headphones Really Designed To Trick You?|first=Mario |last=Aguilar|publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |work=[[Gizmodo]] |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711063936/http://gizmodo.com/are-beats-headphones-really-designed-to-trick-you-1715413621|archivedate=2015-07-11}}</ref> Tests done on an HTC smartphone with Beats Audio indicated that the audio technology is a combination of [[Equalization (audio)|audio equalization]] that boosts the low (bass) and high ends of the audio range,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imgur.com/a/MV0pW|title=What Beats Audio actually does |publisher=Imgur|accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141006142041/http://imgur.com/a/MV0pW|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref> [[Dynamic range compression|audio compression]], and [[Audio power amplifier|audio amplification]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.engadget.com/2011/10/13/htc-sensation-xe-with-beats-audio-review/|title=HTC Sensation XE with Beats Audio review |first=Sharif |last=Sakr|publisher=[[AOL]]|work=[[Engadget]]|accessdate=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150222091408/http://www.engadget.com/2011/10/13/htc-sensation-xe-with-beats-audio-review/ |archivedate=22 February 2015}}</ref> On accusations that Beats' products were \"bass heavy\", Beats current president denies it, citing that their products are not for reference, but rather for playback.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/28287697|title=Beats by Dre president defends headphone bass quality|publisher=BBC Newsbeat |accessdate= 7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150219203409/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/28287697|archivedate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Apple}}\n{{Dr. Dre}}\n\n[[Category:2006 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2006 in technology]]\n[[Category:2010s fashion]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Culver City, California]]\n[[Category:Dr. Dre]]\n[[Category:Audio equipment manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Headphones]]\n[[Category:Headphones manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2008]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:2010 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:2014 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "BeatSkin", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarbuds)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beats_Electronics"}
